<TEXT>
top finance officials from the worlds seven 
largest industrial countries will discuss volatile currency markets 
at a special meeting next month but private economists question 
how successful the session will be 
treasury secretary nicholas brady confirmed on thursday that 
finance ministers and central bank presidents from the united 
states japan west germany britain france italy and canada 
would gather in paris on april 7 
while brady insisted there was no special urgency propelling 
the talks they are coming at a time when the us dollar has been 
rising in value against other currencies in particular the west 
german mark and the japanese yen 
a higher dollar threatens to enlarge an alreadyhuge us trade 
deficit by making foreign products cheaper for americans while 
raising the cost of us goods overseas 
the dollars strength is of great concern to the 
administration said allen sinai chief economist of the boston 
co it constitutes a recession threat because it is a further 
risk to an alreadybeleaguered industrial side of the us 
economy 
while last years trade deficit of 1086 billion was 29 percent 
below the alltime worst deficit of 1521 billion in 1987 
progress in boosting us exports has slowed in recent months 
because of the dollars increases 
brady testifying to a house appropriations subcommittee 
thursday said the administration hoped further gains could be made 
this year in reducing the trade deficit however he conceded that 
progress isnt as fast as i would like it to be 
the dollars advance has occurred despite coordinated 
intervention by the united states and other governments to sell 
dollars on foreign exchange markets and buy other currencies 
some analysts suggested that since government intervention has 
proved largely unsuccessful the officials of the socalled g7 
countries might discuss making coordinated moves to change interest 
rates 
higher interest rates in japan and west germany would tend to 
bolster their currencies while lower interest rates in the united 
states would make dollardenominated investments less attractive 
but such action would need the approval of federal reserve 
chairman alan greenspan who has been resisting administration 
pressure to lower interest rates because of concern about 
inflation greenspan also will attend the paris g7 meeting 
economists also questioned the likelihood of some bold 
initiative to lower the dollars value especially in light of 
bradys general caution in interfering in private market operations 
the g7 process is dead in the water said c fred bergsten 
head of the institute for international economics with exchange 
rates moving in the wrong direction it cries out for more 
effective international coordination 
brady who visited european capitals last week led the effort 
to schedule the special meeting he sees it as an opportunity to 
advance economic coordination among us allies said an 
administration official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
french economics minister pierre beregovoy told reporters in 
paris that he had stressed to brady the need for greater 
cooperation especially in light of the economic problems that 
might arise with the reunification of east and west germany 
some private economists have expressed concern that the 
reunification could prove to be inflationary because of the 
proposal to exchange west germany marks for east german marks on a 
onetoone ratio 
however norbert walker chief economist for deutsche bank the 
largest bank in west germany told reporters in washington that he 
believed reunification could be accomplished without a surge in 
inflation or a big jump in west german interest rates 
walker said increased consumer demand would not trigger higher 
inflation because much of the demand would be met by foreign goods 
helping to lower west germanys large trade surpluses while 
sluggish economic growth in europe would help hold down interest 
rate pressures 
beregovoy said the g7 officials were scheduled to be in paris 
in early april anyway to wrap up details for a new bank for 
european reconstruction and development being created to support 
emerging democracies 
the meeting will occur just one month before a scheduled may 7 
session in washington to coincide with the spring meeting of the 
international monetary fund 
</TEXT>
