federal aids testing experts are encouraged that 
the vast majority of the 2 million people who have been tested for 
the aids virus arent infected even among highrisk groups 
from 1985 to 1989 25 million tests for hiv the virus that 
causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome were performed by 63 
publicly funded prevention programs across the country the 
national centers for disease control said thursday 
of the tests given 149639 or 6 percent were positive the 
cdc said 
out of more than 1 million test subjects in the last two years 
whose aids risk groups were known two groups accounted for more 
than 70 percent the cdc said 
heterosexuals at risk including those with highrisk partners 
or multiple sex partners made up 44 percent and 29 percent were 
heterosexuals who reported no aids risk factors but were tested 
anyway 
fourteen percent were homosexual or bisexual men who make up 
the largest group of aids victims and 9 percent were heterosexual 
intravenous drug abusers the secondleading aids risk group 
positivetest rates were highest for homosexual men who abused 
injectable drugs 17 percent of such test subjects were told they 
were infected the homosexual or bisexual men tested were infected 
at a rate of 165 percent 
still a very high proportion of tested homosexuals and drug 
abusers are not infected said dr stephen bowen deputy 
director at the cdcs center for prevention services 
we still have an opportunity to protect them 
the cdc said that 12 percent to 30 percent of aids tests are 
apparently repeat tests leaving an estimated 2 million people 
tested the cdc said 
in its report the cdc said many of the estimated 1 million 
hivinfected persons in the united states remain unaware of their 
infection of persons who are aware a substantial proportion 
had their infection identified in publicly funded counseling and 
testing programs 
demand for the publicly funded tests has increased from about 
80000 in 1985 to a projected 1 million when 1989 tests are 
totaled bowen said 
health officials dont have a real good handle on the number 
of people who have been tested at private physicians offices not 
participating in the publicly funded aids programs bowen said 
such tests are not necessarily reported to health officials 
more than 120000 aids cases have been reported in the united 
states with more than 72000 deaths 
