<TEXT>
the president of an ohio company accused the 
defense department of spreading false allegations about its work on 
a critical part for missiles without informing the manufacturer of 
the charges 
documents released thursday said the pentagon is investigating 
piqua engineering inc of piqua ohio following charges that 
safety and arming devices produced by the company failed almost 
half of its tests for leaking 
the devices are used on several missiles including the 
sidewinder sparrow standard and patriot 
it is believed that any of the issues can cause premature 
or prevention of detonation of the devices that could result in 
the failure of missiles or other weaponry containing the piqua 
devices said a defense contract administrative message sent to 
army and navy commands in several states 
but john scarbrough sr president of piqua defended his 
companys product and said the pentagon failed to contact him about 
the problems 
the defense criminal investigative service never talked to us 
has never written us a letter at any time scarbrough said in a 
telephone interview they are giving out untrue allegations 
without talking to us 
scarbrough said his 40yearold company has been manufacturing 
safety and arming devices for at least 20 years and has never had a 
single complaint in this instance he believes six disgruntled 
employees are using the government system against the company 
as far as im concerned the allegations are all wrong 
scarbrough said everyone wants to blow the whistle but no one 
wants to check we could have told the defense department if they 
asked us 
pentagon spokeswoman susan hansen said the department would 
neither confirm nor deny an ongoing investigation 
in a jan 30 memorandum the pentagons inspector general office 
warned that the potential may exist for failure of the safety and 
arming devices manufactured by piqua 
this could subsequently impact on the integrity of the weapons 
systems containing these devices wrote william g dupree the 
deputy assistant inspector general for investigations 
the documents were obtained by the project on government 
procurement and released by the independent group to the associated 
press and other news organizations 
piqua employees allegedly have been told not to reject devices 
even if they fail leak tests instead workers are to repair the 
devices using epoxy resin to seal the leaks 
military specifications call for the devices to pass the leak 
tests to ensure that they are sealed and to prevent contamination 
and corrosion 
piqua is believed to have internally experienced as high as a 
50 percent failure rate of safety and arming devices being leak 
tested said the inspector generals document 
the areas most commonly encountering leakage problems are 
either around the window of the device or in the area of the 
electrical connector 
scarbrough said that after initial checks the failure rate was 
less than 1 percent and when they leave here they dont leak at 
all information on the tests have been substantiated by three 
defense department inspectors at the ohio plant he said 
the inspector generals memo also said questions have been 
raised about holes in the device to which detonators and detonator 
sleeves are attached 
it is believed the holes cannot correctly accept the 
detonators and sleeves and that piqua utilizes unauthorized repair 
and rework procedures to correct the problem the document said 
the memo said there had been allegations that employees were 
told to use hand tools to enlarge holes that were too small and 
resorted to unapproved oversized detonators on holes that were too 
large 
