<TEXT>
the senate in its first major vote on a 
compromise clean air bill rejected a proposal to tighten controls 
on toxic air pollution thursday night after senate leaders said it 
threatened their agreement with the white house 
the vote to kill the amendment was 6533 
senate leaders later put off a vote on a proposal by sen robert 
byrd dw va to help coal miners who lose their jobs because of 
tougher pollution controls the 700 million safety net for 
miners was strongly opposed by the bush administration 
sen bob dole rkan said passage of the byrd amendment would 
jeopardize the compromise agreement with the administration and 
could lead to no clean air bill being approved by the senate 
the senators adjourned early today and would resume 
consideration of the bill later in the day 
the amendment on tougher controls on toxic chemicals from 
automobiles was one of a string of strengthening provisions 
expected to be brought to the floor by senators arguing the 
compromise legislation isnt strong enough 
the vote was seen as an indicator on the strength of support for 
a compromise worked out by senate leaders and the bush 
administration to ease senate approval for the first toughening of 
federal air pollution controls in 13 years 
sen frank lautenberg dnj called his amendment necessary to 
protect citizens from cancercausing chemicals noting more than 
half of such chemical releases come from automobiles trucks and 
buses 
but the measure opposed by the bush administration because of 
its reported 15 billion price tag was described by sen max 
baucus dmont as a deal breaker meaning its passage would 
cause a compromise agreement with the bush adminstration on clean 
air to fall apart 
if this amendment passes the deal will be off the deal will 
be busted and there very well could be no clean air act said 
baucus a floor manager for the bill shortly before the vote 
both senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine and sen 
bob dole rkan the minority leader asked that the amendment be 
rejected 
the senate throughout the day wrestled with a stream of 
amendments and more were expected 
a number of senators unveiled proposals earlier thursday for 
more stringent provisions many aimed at automobiles 
lautenberg whose amendment was among those unveiled told 
reporters we know the odds are heavy against us 
the clean air measure represents the first tightening of federal 
air pollution control laws in 13 years it calls for sweeping curbs 
on smogcausing pollution from automobiles and industrial plants 
and requires new cuts in acid rain pollutants from coalfired 
electric power plants 
a similar bill remains in committee in the house 
in earlier floor action thursday the senators 
approved by voice vote a requirement that the environmental 
protection agency take into account carbon dioxide emissions which 
contribute to global warming when making urban transportation flow 
studies 
approved 8016 an amendment that requires that hcfcs or 
hydrochlorofluorocarbons be phased out by 2030 the hcfcs can 
sometimes subsitute for cfcs or chlorofluorocarbons chemicals that 
are widely used in refrigeration and other areas but cause damage 
to the earths protective ozone layer 
hcfcs typically have only about 5 percent of the 
ozonedestroying potential of the most common cfcs critics of 
their use have cautioned that they still pose a threat to ozone 
depletion if relied on permanently 
meanwhile an amendment requiring automakers to increase fuel 
efficiency by setting limits on carbon dioxide emissions was 
withdrawn by its sponsor sen richard bryan dnev the measure 
had been vigorously opposed by the auto industry and the white 
house and deleted from an early draft of the bill 
the lautenberg amendment was the first of a series of 
strengthening amendments that are expected to be offered by 
senators who believe the senatewhite house compromise weakened key 
parts of the original senate bill 
the proposed amendments still to be considered would tighten 
controls on smogcausing pollution from automobiles and industrial 
sources in urban areas as well as expanding the use of alternative 
cleanburning fuels 
the amendments would expand the cities that would have to meet 
pollution standards through the use of cleaner fuels require fleet 
operators to use clean burning fuels impose a second round of auto 
tailpipe emission standards in the year 2003 and broaden the 
number of businesses that would have to comply with smogrelated 
pollution controls so small polluters are included 
another amendment in the package would reinstate in the bill a 
requirement that the environmental protection agency impose a 
pollution control program if a city fails to enact one the epa 
currently has the authority 
