<TEXT>
a major factor behind the nations infant 
mortality rate low birth weight is headed the wrong way after 
10 years of improvement according to federal experts in infant 
health 
the rate of low birth weight rose 2 percent from 1985 to 1987 
the latest year for which statistics are available after a 9 
percent drop from 1975 to 1985 the national centers for disease 
control reported thursday 
sixtynine out of 1000 babies born in 1987 were under 5 pounds 
considered low birth weight compared with 675 out of 1000 in 
1985 the 1987 figures nonetheless are improved from 739 
reported in 1975 
the rate of babies born at very low birth weight below 3 
pounds 4 ounces is rising even faster up 68 percent from 1975 
to 1987 the report said in 1987 124 out of every 1000 births 
was below 3 pounds 4 ounces compared with 116 in 1975 
this rate is a small proportion of births but its 
increasing which makes it more difficult in the future to improve 
our infant mortality rate said dr carol hogue director of the 
cdcs division of reproductive health 
improvements in the nations infant mortality rate in the past 
two decades are largely because of improved means of keeping 
premature babies alive not because of improved infant health she 
said 
were not sure we can continue to improve infant mortality by 
improving this very expensive technology she said we really 
need to focus on reducing the incidence of low birth weight 
babies weighing less than 3 pounds 4 ounces are 90 to 100 times 
more likely to die in their first year than other babies she said 
infants under 5 pounds run at least a five times greater risk of 
death than babies of normal weight about 6 to 9 pounds 
the rate of low birth weight among black infants is more than 
twice the rate for white infants 1271 per 1000 blacks in 1987 
compared with 568 for whites the disparity has widened since 15 
years ago when the rates were 1309 for blacks and 626 for whites 
low birth weight rose less than 1 percent for whites between 
1985 and 1987 but 2 percent for blacks 
the atlantabased cdc called the reasons behind the blackwhite 
gap complex more black women are in highrisk groups for 
underweight babies poor unmarried under 20 poorly educated or 
lacking proper prenatal care the agency said 
other factors include poor nutritional status closetogether 
pregnancies and higher rates of unwanted births the cdc said more 
than 16 percent of underweight black babies were unwanted or 
mistimed pregnancies the cdc said 
most low birthweight babies are premature babies nearly six in 
10 are born earlier than 37 weeks of pregnancy compared with the 
standard 40 weeks each year some 35 million babies are born in 
the united states 
