before a senate agriculture subcommittee but conceded that wheat 
prices probably would drop initially if farmers nationwide were 
given more flexibility in choosing which crops they grow 
bruce gardner usda assistant secretary for economics projected 
that up to 3 million additional wheat acres would be planted if the 
administrations proposal were implemented in 1991 wheat prices 
could fall as much as 1520 cents a bushel he said 
wheat prices are projected to average 380 to 390 a bushel in 
the 1990 crop year according to usda 
however gardner said wheat producers are going to be 
protected by federal subsidies from a drop in their incomes 
overall he contended that farmers would benefit from more planting 
flexibility because they could adjust their cropping patterns to 
take advantage of potential higher prices in the markets 
