<TEXT>
an unprecedented statement by president bush 
opposing the settlement of soviet jewish refugees in east jerusalem 
could make it more difficult for the israeli cabinet to approve 
us proposals for mideast negotiations this weekend 
by coupling east jerusalem with the west bank and gaza as 
offlimits to settlers bush appeared to question israels 
retention of the predominantly arab part of the city 
all week us officials have danced around bushs statement 
insisting there is no change in us policy on jerusalem or on the 
west bank and gaza they voiced approval of jews living in both the 
predominantly jewish and mostly arab parts of the city 
but many questions were left unanswered in fact new questions 
were raised 
a white house statement on jerusalem on monday for instance 
said us policy backs the right of jews as well as others to 
live there in the context of a negotiated settlement 
that suggests jews who have lived in jerusalem for more than 
3000 years need arab acquiescence to remain in the older part of 
the city 
on friday white house press secretary marlin fitzwater having 
tried all week to persuade reporters there was no change in policy 
admitted there are some words you cant use in describing this 
policy and some words you can use 
the spokesman insisted there is no special motivation behind 
the presidents words there was no special purpose or attention 
there 
a twicepostponed showdown in the israeli cabinet is now set for 
sunday when the cabinet takes up a formula by secretary of state 
james a baker iii that has split the conservative likud and the 
dovish labor parties 
bakers goal is to have israelis meet with palestinians in cairo 
as the first step toward settlement without a dialogue between 
israelis and palestinians we can never move forward to peace he 
said tuesday 
bakers formula tries to bridge differences between israel on 
the one hand and egypt and the palestine liberation organization 
on the other it would permit a palestinian arab resident of east 
jerusalem and one or two palestinians deported by israel from the 
west bank to participate in the talks 
but israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir and other leaders of 
the likud coalition are worried that might clear a way for the plo 
to dominate the agenda 
labor on the other hand is impatient to proceed with 
negotiations 
amid this political debate first baker and then bush made 
statements that stirred controversy in israel and may have hardened 
likuds resistance to the us formula 
baker told a house subcommittee last week the administration 
wanted assurances a us 400 million housing loan guarantee would 
not be used to settle soviet jewish refugees on the west bank 
only about 100 of the thousands of jews who have poured into 
israel have been settled on the west bank but their presence is 
taken by the arabs as evidence that israel does not intend to 
relinquish the territory 
bakers thrust at shamirs settlement program irritated the 
prime minister and members of both likud and labor were upset by 
bakers statement at the same hearing that there is no evidence plo 
chairman yasser arafat is violating his december 1988 renunciation 
of terrorism 
then at a news conference saturday in palm springs calif the 
president weighed in with a statement opposing new settlements on 
the west bank or in east jerusalem 
his intention may have been to discourage israel from expanding 
east jerusalem to its suburbs and to settle soviet jews there 
that would have been consistent with longstanding us policy 
against further jewish settlements on the west bank as an obstacle 
to mideast negotiations 
but bush by linking east jerusalem and the west bank may have 
had something else in mind that he considers east jerusalem 
occupied territory and jews living there as settlers as well 
the president had not been asked about east jerusalem and his 
statement upset israelis who see the predominantly arab part of 
their capital and the west bank as completely different 
many israelis would surrender most of the west bank as part of a 
peace agreement with the arabs but very few would be willing to 
relinquish any part of their capital 
in more than two decades of us diplomacy jerusalem and the 
west bank have been approached as separate issues jerusalem is 
touchier and american presidents and secretaries of state have 
tried to keep their distance usually by saying ambiguously that 
the city should never be divided again and not saying whether 
israel ought to retain exclusive control over jerusalem 
bushs statement is a problem then 
the white house and state department tried on wednesday to 
soften its impact by asserting support for jews living in jerusalem 
and insisting us policy on the city and on the west bank had not 
changed 
maybe it has and maybe it hasnt that depends on what bush has 
in mind 
but gaining israels approval sunday of bakers formula for 
negotiations is now tougher than ever 
