<TEXT>
hughes aircraft co admitted friday that 
it unlawfully obtained classified pentagon budget documents and 
agreed to pay the government 367 million officials said 
hughes which pleaded guilty to two felony counts is the fourth 
major defense contractor to admit to such charges three to six 
other pentagon contractors remain under investigation said michael 
j costello special agent in charge of the defense criminal 
investigative services washington field office 
the two counts against hughes concern fiveyear defense program 
documents issued in 1983 and 1984 summarizing resources planned 
programmed and budgeted by the department of defense according to 
a statement by susan j crawford the pentagons inspector general 
the documents were classified secret and they were not 
releasable to defense department contractors the statement said 
hughes through former employee frank j caso unlawfully 
acquired these and other classified pentagon documents from 
employees of other defense contractors between 1978 and 1985 
according to a statement from us attorney henry e hudson of the 
eastern district of virginia 
caso has not been charged said costello who added that he 
could not confirm nor deny whether caso was the subject of a 
criminal investigation 
the crawford statement said hughes tried to hide the fact that 
it had the documents before 1978 hughes did not enter the 
documents into its classified document accountability system from 
1978 through 1985 the documents were logged into the system but 
not under their actual titles in an attempt to hide their 
receipt the statement said 
richard dore a spokesman for the los angelesbased hughes did 
not immediately return a phone call seeking comment on the case 
hughes agreed to pay 355 million in settlement of any civil 
liability which may arise out of its actions plus 50000 for 
investigative costs 50000 from its overhead account and a total 
of 20000 in penalties stemming from the actual charges each 
charge carries a maximum penalty of 10000 
the company will make the payment within five days according to 
the plea agreement entered before us district judge james c 
cacheris 
costello said he was not certain how much money if any hughes 
earned because of its access to the documents 
we would have to make an assumption that they did make 
money he said thats the reason for the 35 million 
settlement 
negotiations with hughes had been under way for several months 
he said 
the probe of defense contractors begun in the mid1980s and 
codenamed operation uncover has resulted in guilty pleas from 
three other major defense contractors as well gte government 
systems division the boeing company and rca corp costello said 
the investigation has been carried out by dcis the defense 
department inspector generals investigative arm 
gte paid about 300000 in fines in 1985 he said 
the boeing company paid fines and restitution of 52 million 
and a boeing employee richard lee fowler was convicted last 
december of 39 counts of conspiracy conveyance without authority 
conversion and mail fraud and sentenced to two years in prison the 
hudson statement said 
on feb 5 rca corp was ordered to pay fines and restitution of 
275 million and former rca employee leonard kampf and current 
rca employee ronald stevens each pleaded guilty to one felony count 
of conveyance without authority each faces up to 10 years in 
prison and fines of up to 10000 sentencing for the two is 
scheduled for april 6 the hudson statement said 
