<TEXT>
the wampanoag indians who have lived on 
these red cliffs for centuries follow a simple creed that explains 
how they regained 400 acres and successfully battled jacqueline 
onassis in a decadeold land dispute 
they call it iootash meaning stand firm a word that 
was relayed to tribal members by the legendary chief annawon when 
the pilgrims arrived in 1620 
that philosophy has sustained them over the years spurring 
their fight for valuable acreage here that they say is of 
historical significance to the tribe they also ended the fight 
with mrs onassis last week when she agreed to give them a larger 
piece of land and 100000 in exchange for their shares of a tiny 
beachfront site on marthas vineyard that figures in tribal legend 
we tend to be stubborn said donald widdiss president of 
the wampanoag tribal council we tend to think very seriously 
about strategy and about what we want 
there may be only about 250 wampanoags on the island just south 
of cape cod but the tribe is tenacious the wampanoags were eking 
out a living on the clay cliffs around 1100 when leif erickson 
became the first white man to make contact with them 
some tribal members fought mrs onassis attempt to buy them out 
of the 15 acre site a tangled web of litigation that began in 
1980 mrs onassis owned a onesixth share of the land which is 
surrounded by her 400acre estate 
but 25 wampanoags the descendants of william vanderhoop an 
original owner of the site were determined to get another piece of 
land in exchange tribal legend has it that the site is where the 
great chief moshup threw his children into the sea when he foresaw 
the coming of the white man 
we didnt want to give up something that had belonged to our 
greatgreat grandfather said thelma vanderhoop weissberg 62 in 
an interview at her home after the settlement was announced 
wednesday in dukes county probate court 
i have a very special feeling about the land here its a 
feeling only an indian can have it was important we get more land 
in return not just money 
charlie vanderhoop 68 who was born at the gay head lighthouse 
when his father was the lighthouse keeper stood on the cliffs a 
few hours after the onassis settlement and pointed at a stretch of 
ocean known as the devils den in wampanoag lore 
everything here means something to me said vanderhoop i 
want to keep as much land as we can for our children 
the wampanoags have made their living from the sea for 
centuries not long ago it was whaling and swordfishing now those 
who can afford boats go shellfishing many of the women work in 
souvenir shops on the picturesque cliffs 
just how tough the wampanoags were was made clear in 1974 when 
they filed suit against the town of gay head for land they said was 
tribal property they claimed that the 1790 indian nonintercourse 
act forbidding transfer of indian lands without federal approval 
was violated in the 1870s when the state redistributed tribal lands 
to residents 
they won the land settlement several years ago just as they 
received federal recognition as a tribe the wampanoag were given 
45 million to buy back land in gay head 
beatrice gentry 79 another member of the vanderhoop family 
initiated the first lawsuits in the 1970s 
we wanted the land because its part of our culture said 
gentry who worked her way through college by making pots from the 
cliffs clay 
gay head on the southwestern tip of marthas vineyard is one 
of the poorest communities in the state although its just a few 
miles up the beach from the sprawling shingled summer homes of the 
wealthy and the wellknown during the past 100 years only two 
nonindians have been elected to the town council 
many wampanoag are wary of outsiders and some believe all the 
land in gay head should be returned to them they refuse to use the 
term pilgrims to describe the early white settlers 
they were invaders said widdiss 
