china has bought an additional 396300 metric 
tons of us wheat under a price subsidy program the agriculture 
department said friday 
f paul dickerson general sales manager for the departments 
foreign agricultural service said two private exporting companies 
made the deals under the departments export enhancement program 
or eep 
delivery of the wheat is scheduled for july and august he said 
the sales were part of 1 million tons authorized china under eep 
on feb 8 previous allocations had been exhausted except for 1050 
tons 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels 
of wheat the latest sales would be about 145 million bushels at 
current prices estimated by usda at around 4 per bushel the wheat 
would have a farm value of around 58 million 
under eep arrangements private exporters can sell us 
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in 
selected overseas markets and then collect free government 
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or subsidies 
dickerson said the latest subsidies averaged 443 per ton or 
about 12 cents per bushel 
the subsidized sales were handled by mitsubishi international 
corp 30000 tons and continental grain co 366300 tons 
with the latest sales china has bought about 700000 tons of 
us wheat for delivery in the 199091 wheat marketing year that 
will begin june 1 compared with more than 57 million tons in 
198990 
