tax laws enacted in 1978 and 1981 cut taxes significantly for the 
wealthiest americans but not nearly so much for those who earn less 
rostenkowski in a statement on the new report said the 
reduction in tax burdens for the wealthy was staggering 
the cbo conclusion is essentially the same as that in a study by 
citizens for tax justice that was made public thursday that study 
found if tax laws were made as fair today as they were in 1977 all 
but the richest 10 percent would pay less and the government would 
still collect 675 billion a year more 
the bush administration prefers to point out to figures showing 
the richest americans pay a greater share of the total tax burden 
than they were in 1977 congressional economists agree but say 
thats because incomes of the wealthiest 10 percent have soared 
during the same period 
