<TEXT>
members of congress scolded the bush 
administration friday for failing to meet the deadline for setting 
out regulations to assure the quality and accuracy of all medical 
laboratory tests 
lawmakers were not appeased by the health care financing 
administrations announcement that final rules to bring 12000 
medical labs under uniform national testing standards would be 
published next week and could go into effect after a 60day comment 
period 
by hcfas own estimate there are between 300000 and 600000 
medical testing facilities including labs in physicians offices 
employer health units public health departments blood banks and 
public screening labs most of those would be covered by other 
rules hcfa is drafting but has not yet formally proposed 
it is critical that all laboratories be regulated said sen 
brock adams dwash each month the implementation is 
delayed more cases of cancer go undetected more men and women 
receive erroneous laboratory reports and more tragedies result 
we need a sense of urgency added sen barbara mikulski 
dmd at the joint hearing of the senate labor and human resources 
committee and the governmental affairs subcommittee on oversight of 
government management 
gail wilensky who recently took over as head of hcfa told the 
lawmakers the rules covering 12000 labs that receive payments from 
medicare and medicaid will make a tremendous difference in the 
way those labs operate 
she said those rules were already being drafted when congress 
passed a law in 1988 giving hcfa authority to regulate all testing 
labs and directing the agency to have rules in place to implement 
the law by jan 1 1990 
the main reason for the delay in meeting that deadline she 
said was major unexpected dissension within the scientific 
community over which tests should be subject to the least 
regulation because of their simplicity and low risk to the patient 
and which ones should meet tougher standards 
she said hcfa expected to propose rules to meet the 1988 law in 
three stages the first set of rules which she expected to be 
proposed by midapril would define three levels of testing and the 
personnel quality assurance and proficiency testing requirements 
for each level 
pressed by lawmakers to estimate when the law would be fully 
implemented wilensky said it would depend on how many comments the 
agency receives on the proposals but that she hoped it would be 
within two years 
lawmakers have been particularly concerned about pap tests used 
to detect cervical cancer reports about inaccuracies in these 
tests helped spur passage of the 1988 law rep carl levin 
dmich estimated that up to 40 percent of pap test results are 
done incorrectly 
wilensky said 75 percent of pap tests are performed by the 
12000 labs that will soon be regulated but leven said that will 
still leave as many as 20 million pap tests each year being read by 
unregulated labs 
thats still a huge number waiting for some kind of 
assurance levin said 
under the regulations hcfa expects to propose next month some 
tests would be waived from regulation because they are simple low 
risk and have little margin for error rep ron wyden dore who 
testified at the hearing said he was concerned that tests for 
strep throat sickle cell anemia blood clotting and gonorrhea 
would be exempt 
cholesterol screening would be subject to a higher level of 
oversight and regulation because the test is more complex and 
involves a greater degree of risk to the patient if performed 
incorrectly wilensky said 
the highest level of regulation would be imposed for tests such 
as the pap smear and for aids infection she said 
