tree limbs were stacked head high along 
curbs in many des moines neighborhoods friday as the metropolitan 
area cleaned up from what the state climatologist said may have 
been the ice storm of the century 
two days after central iowa was glazed with thick ice 
temperatures were in the 60s and rivers were rising 
the storm stuck at least an inch of ice on tree limbs and power 
lines wednesday cutting electrical service to 91000 customers 
more than half of the metropolitan area iowa power spokesman chuck 
seel said the company hoped the remaining customers would be hooked 
up by sunday 
the utility had restored power to all but about 14000 customers 
by friday morning 
were tickled to death at how well its gone seel said 
a lot of those who are without service have the toughest 
repairs he said such as service lines ripped out of houses by 
falling limbs 
hundreds of linemen and their boom trucks were brought in from 
other cities and nearly all were working double shifts 
there are at least 330 linemen or tree men out there and 150 
worked through the night seel said 
state climatologist harry hillaker said other ice storms have 
caused damage but none were as severe 
ive checked other storms that were called the worst of this 
century and this one was more widespread he said 
rivers were swollen with runoff friday as the ice melted but no 
flooding was reported 
the storm also iced sections of states north and west of iowa 
two days earlier it dumped as much as 50 inches of snow on colorado 
and wyoming major highways in southeastern wyoming werent 
reopened until late thursday 
des moines and its suburbs urged homeowners to haul tree limbs 
broken by the weight of the ice out to the curb where they would 
