<TEXT>
the senate armed services committee has voted 
to grant the pentagon part of the authority to transfer money to 
military personnel accounts and avert massive layoffs the panels 
chairman said friday 
but the action should have little overall effect on the 
departments request since rep les aspin dwis chairman of the 
house armed services committee has refused to take up the issue in 
his panel 
such shifting of funds must be approved by the house and senate 
armed services panels and the house and senate appropriations 
committees 
the defense department originally asked congress for the 
authority to transfer 935 million from weapons and other accounts 
to personnel to avoid laying off tens of thousands of men and 
women freezing promotions and holding up transfers 
the drastic steps are required under the grammrudman 
deficitreduction law 
but aspin said president bush could have exempted personnel from 
the law back on aug 15 as past administrations have done and 
declined to take up the pentagons request 
putting weapons before people was their decision and now 
theyre stuck with it aspin said late last month 
nevertheless the senate committee voted in executive session 
thursday to approve 85 percent of the pentagons request or 795 
million from weapons to personnel accounts 
the action would force the defense department to take some 
voluntary steps including reducing the number of new recruits 
during the rest of fiscal 1990 and allowing some people to leave 90 
days before their service ends 
the department would be spared involuntary adverse personnel 
actions 
we voted on the side of the men and women in the military who 
were put at risk by the administrations decision not to use its 
authority to exempt the military personnel accounts sen sam 
nunn dga the armed services chairman said in a speech on the 
senate floor friday 
in a related development aspin said friday significant cuts in 
defense spending are possible over the next several years but 
initial cuts will have to be small 
a concerted and strategic effort is needed to restructure our 
armed forces consistent with the imperative to buy the right 
combination of forces equipment operational readiness and 
research in this time of great change and uncertainity he said 
in a letter to the rep leon panetta dcalif chairman of the 
house budget committee aspin declined to reveal his overall figure 
for the fiscal 1991 defense budget 
the bush administration has proposed a budget of 3067 billion 
including funds for defense the department of energy and military 
construction 
in a republican response to aspins letter rep william 
dickinson rala expressed his support for the administrations 
budget and warned against deep cuts in defense spending 
although most of us feel more secure when assessing soviet 
military intentions soviet military capability even after the 
pending cfe and start agreements are concluded remains 
formidable said dickinson the panels ranking gop member 
nunn in a letter to the senate budget committee said he 
couldnt provide an overall figure for the fiscal 1991 defense 
budget because the pentagon hasnt produced a comprehensive 
fiveyear defense plan 
in addition nunn noted the pentagon is currently reviewing 
several bigticket programs such as the b2 stealth bomber the 
c17 transport plane and the strategic defense initiative 
in order for the armed services committee and the whole 
congress to make decisions on the fiscal 1991 defense budget we 
must have a clear picture of where our defense policies are going 
over the next three to five years nunn said in a threepage 
letter 
</TEXT>
