<TEXT>
an official from the us embassy in moscow 
testified friday that a terrorist warning prior to the december 
1988 bombing of pan am flight 103 was widely distributed to 
americans in moscow and given to soviet officials 
the state department previously acknowledged only that the 
notice was improperly posted in the embassy a week before flight 
103 blew up over lockerbie scotland killing 270 people 
officials said the posting violated a policy against notifying 
government workers when other prospective passengers are not told 
of a threat 
raymond f smith who was acting deputy chief of mission in 
moscow at the time told the presidential commission on aviation 
security and terrorism that he felt a moral obligation to let 
people know about the threat against pan am flights between 
frankfurt and the united states 
smith said in sworn testimony that he knew of no other embassy 
that disseminated the notice publicly state department officials 
have said the threat turned out to be a hoax orginating in 
helsinki finland despite the fact it fit the lockerbie bombing 
smith said embassy officials decided in a toplevel staff 
meeting to give the notice the widest distribution possible 
posting it at several strategic places around the compound and 
sending it to a company that contracted workz 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
to the soviet government 
the official who is now moscow embassy political counsellor 
said he also notified the federal aviation administration which 
had originated the advisory that the notice was being posted and 
received no response 
the embassy notice said employees were left to their own 
discretion on whether to change travel plans but noted they still 
were required to fly on an american carrier pan am was the only 
us carrier flying out of moscow although other airlines could be 
used from europe to the united states 
also at the hearing the commission disclosed a telex from pan 
ams moscow office saying that 80 percent of moscow passengers were 
changing their bookings as a result of the posted threat 
but the official who sent the internal telex the airlines 
former moscow manager jennifer s young testified that she had no 
direct knowledge of any cancelations and used the 80percent figure 
to give her missive more impact 
ms young said a parttime reservations clerk at pan ams office 
in the embassy had told her there were several inquiries about the 
notice and she got the impression there also were cancelations 
commission chairwoman ann mclaughlin said the panel staff has 
yet to find hard evidence of any changes in bookings as a result of 
the threat but has asked pan am for passenger data and is 
continuing its investigation 
