<TEXT>
many israelis are lured to 
the west bank by cheap land low or interestfree mortgages and the 
desire for the space they lack in most of the countrys crowded 
cities 
such benefits have played a significant role in attracting 
75000 jews to 143 settlements in the past two decades they are 
also a selling point in efforts by settlement leaders to attract 
soviet jews who are flooding into israel 
a new controversy erupted over the settlements following prime 
minister yitzhak shamirs suggestion which he quickly withdrew 
that israel might need the land captured in the 1967 middle east 
war for settling tens of thousands of new soviet immigrants 
his remark set off arab fears of israel annexing the occupied 
west bank and gaza strip and prompted us warnings that israel 
would not receive 400 million in requested housing guarantees if 
it settled soviet jews on occupied land 
shamir stressed there was no policy of settling soviet jews in 
occupied areas and there are no special incentives beyond 
those given to development towns in remote areas of israel where 
tax breaks are provided to encourage growth and industry 
israel harel editor of the settler magazine nekuda said a 
drive to bring soviet immigrants to the territories has been 
without much success 
he said that only about 200 have been placed in the west bank 
and even they had not made a final decision to live there 
the reasons varied most of the settlements are religious and 
the immigrants are secular they like to go to cities not small 
villages like ours the intefadeh uprising doesnt help the 
cause either he said 
meron benvenisti an exdeputy mayor of jerusalem who has 
studied the territories for a decade said even without new 
enticements existing benefits for any west bank settler were 
considerable 
he estimated the government and the world zionist organization 
have spent 25 billion in the past 20 years building and 
maintaining the settlements 
the government has paid for roads lighting and other site 
preparations it also allocates more money per pupil to educate 
settlement children and covers the cost of their busing benvenisti 
said 
settlers enjoy a 7 percent reduction in income taxes and 
industries opening in the territories receive a 40 percent grant 
for the purchase of equipment he said 
also benvenisti said the israel lands authority sells settlers 
building plots from land expropriated from arabs for 5 percent of 
the assessed value about 40 percent of the west bank was taken 
over by the state under a 1980 decree that expropriated all 
unregistered and uncultivated land 
settlement leaders are eager to recruit and have mounted a 
campaign to attract both soviet immigrants and nativeborn israelis 
