<TEXT>
taiwans justice chief said friday he will 
drop his challenge to president lee tenghui in this months 
presidential election defusing a crisis that threatened to split 
the ruling party 
the announcement leaves a clear path to election for lee who 
was endorsed last month as the official candidate of the ruling 
nationalist party 
the partys elder members are uncomfortable with lee a native 
taiwanese because they fear he does not share their intense desire 
to return to the chinese mainland and believe he is trying to amass 
too much power 
lin yangkang the popular 62yearold judiciary chief made the 
announcement he would drop from the race after a 20minute meeting 
with eight party veterans who lee had asked to find a resolution to 
the political battle 
i decided that i should not do anything to hurt the nation and 
peoples welfare lin told reporters afterward 
about 200 aging members of the electoral college had thrown 
their support behind lin for president and chiang wego the sole 
surviving son of nationalist leader chiang kaishek for vice 
president 
the 752seat electoral college known as the national assembly 
is dominated by politicians who fled the chinese mainland to taiwan 
with the rest of the nationalist government in 1949 after losing a 
civil war to communist forces 
they have not faced reelection since then frozen in office to 
support the nationalist governments claim to still be the 
legitimate ruler of all china 
lin said he would soon ask the elderly politicians to drop the 
idea of endorsing him i was told that people felt uneasy about 
the emergence of a second ticket in the election because it would 
force them to take sides 
the official radio reported that lee thanked lin for his 
decision the electoral college is expected to officially chose the 
president march 21 
lee 66 succeeded president chiang chingkuo when he died in 
office in 1987 the late president was another son of chiang 
kaishek 
china made a public expression of concern over the political 
bickering this week but it was not clear if those statements 
affected fridays developments beijing which seeks reunification 
with taiwan condemned the instability caused by the 
nationalist rift 
chiang wego viewed by many of the older assemblymen as the 
defender of their dream of returning to the mainland was not 
available friday for comment in the past he has said he would not 
actively campaign but would not discourage the electoral college 
from supporting him 
a fire meanwhile broke out in the national legislature friday 
and police blamed activists who want taiwan to drop its claim to be 
chinas legitimate government 
police said the early morning blaze may have been caused by 
firebombs several reception rooms were reported damaged 
nearby police discovered a fence painted with the slogan 
burn chinese pirates to death strive for taiwanese 
independence and bloodbath taiwan the references were 
apparently to elderly members of the yuan taiwans highest 
lawmaking body who fled mainland china decades ago 
less than an hour later a blaze occurred at the faculty 
dormitory at national taiwan university with similar slogans left 
behind 
no one was reported injured in either fire and there was no 
claim of responsibility 
also friday chiang hsiaowu son of late president chiang 
chingkuo said he would resign as head of taiwans mission to 
japan because he was disappointed over our leaders fighting over 
power without any regard to the nations future 
he criticized chiang wego for wanting to be elected but 
claiming he would not campaign but he said he would not waste 
my time to persuade his uncle to pull out of the race 
in an effort to placate his critics president lee said 
wednesday that party members would be consulted over whether he 
should continue as party chairman as well as head of government 
newspapers reported that lin backed by the aging conservatives 
wants lee to step down as party chairman to allow a collective 
leadership after the presidential election 
the 3yearold opposition democratic progressive party does not 
have enough members in the national assembly to nominate its own 
candidate for president it has demanded all the mainland chinese 
assemblymen retire and that the president be chosen by popular 
election 
