<TEXT>
sperm banks keep records so detailed its 
unlikely a bank is to blame in the case of a white woman who says 
she was impregnated with a black mans sperm rather than her dying 
husbands experts said friday 
but if the nations three dozen major sperm banks are as safe as 
savings banks they arent nearly as regulated new york is the 
only state to license sperm banks and the federal government lacks 
control over them 
the issue arose this week after it was disclosed a new york 
woman is suing a fertility clinic and a sperm bank claiming her 
late husbands sperm was switched with that of a black man 
the woman says that after she was fertilized with the sperm she 
gave birth to a girl who appears to be half black 
david gould the attorney for the queens resident asked that 
her name be withheld because of emotional distress the girl now 
3 has been taunted because she doesnt look like her parents 
in 1985 the couple paid idant laboratories the nations oldest 
and largest commercial sperm bank to store the husbands sperm he 
had cancer and the couple feared chemotherapy could damage his 
sperm such concerns idant says account for about half its 
deposits 
the woman later contacted advanced fertility services to get the 
sperm samples from idant and use them for insemination 
advanced says the sperm it used came from idant idant says the 
sperm it sent was definitely the husbands and couldnt be the 
sperm that impregnated the wife 
dr jerome sherman chairman of american association of tissue 
banks reproductive council said sperm banks identification 
procedures are designed to avoid such confusion 
the chance of this happening is extremely remote if not 
impossible he said ive visited that facility idant and 
seen their identification procedures it couldnt be run any 
better as far as labeling is concerned 
it was much more likely he said that a woman lodging such a 
complaint had sexual intercourse with someone other than the sperm 
donor 
steven salzman another attorney for the woman denied shermans 
suggestion but said it was not yet clear if fault rested with the 
fertility clinic or the sperm bank 
at most sperm banks a man ejaculates into a container that is 
marked with his personal identification code and the date then it 
is tested divided into small units placed in small plastic 
straws and frozen 
the straws are lodged inside an aluminum container that looks 
like a cigar tube which also bears a label with the donors code 
it in turn is placed in a large tank of liquid nitrogen which 
keeps the sperm at minus 320 degrees 
meanwhile a log of the sperms history when how and where it 
was donated tested frozen and stored is compiled any 
withdrawal also is marked down an inventory of all sperm deposits 
is taken periodically 
in the case at issue idant says its records show the sperm it 
sent to the clinic was the husbands five straws are gone from 
his cigar tube and no one elses straws are missing and that a 
test showed the babys dna didnt match the husbands 
sherman a university of arkansas medicine professor who directs 
a sperm bank in little rock said his facility stores donor sperm 
of different races in different vaults idant uses colored plastic 
straws to indicate a donors race 
you have had situations where technicians have goofed and the 
semen was thawed but mixups like the one this woman claims 
never sherman said 
william andrews medical director of the american fertility 
society said the labeling errors that periodically complicate 
blood transfusions dont crop up in artificial inseminations 
because sperm banks arent responding to emergencies and have more 
time to double and crosscheck 
he also noted that since the vast majority of sperm samples are 
donated by whites the odds against a switch like the one alleged 
are particularly long 
given the absence of government regulation however consumers 
must be sure a sperm bank follows recordkeeping procedures 
recommended by the federal center for disease control and the 
fertility association 
mary anne gardineer of the state health department said the new 
york sperm bank regulations that took effect in october werent 
prompted by any problem but by a concern that inadequate screening 
of anonymous sperm donors might lead to the transmission of aids 
she said she had never heard of any mixup like the one alleged 
in the lawsuit but said her department would review the 
regulations to see if a more definitive identification of a donors 
sperm should be required 
her colleague dr jean linden concurred as in any other 
form of banking record keeping is very very important 
</TEXT>
