<TEXT>
an estimated 2 million people have been tested 
for aids in publicly funded programs and at least 6 percent were 
found to be among the million or so americans believed infected 
experts said thursday 
from 1985 to 1989 25 million tests for hiv the virus that 
causes aids were performed by 63 publicly funded prevention 
programs across the country the centers for disease control 
reported 
of the tests given 149639 or 6 percent were positive 
considering that between 12 percent and 30 percent of aids tests 
are apparently repeat tests that leaves an estimated 2 million 
people tested with 123000 or 6 percent to 145000 of them 
infected the cdc said 
one of the things that surprises me is how many people have 
elected to learn their aidsvirus antibody status and what they 
can do to protect themselves said dr stephen bowen deputy 
director for hiv in the cdcs center for prevention services 
many of the estimated 1 million people overall infected with hiv 
are unaware of their infection the atlantabased cdc said in its 
weekly report 
out of more than 1 million people tested in the last two years 
whose aids risk groups were known 44 percent were heterosexuals at 
risk including those with highrisk partners or multiple sex 
partners and 29 percent were heterosexuals who reported no aids 
risk factors but were tested anyway 
fourteen percent were homosexual or bisexual men who make up 
the largest group of aids victims and 9 percent were heterosexual 
intravenous drug abusers the secondleading aids risk group 
positivetest rates were highest for gay men who abused 
injectable drugs 17 percent of such test subjects were told they 
were infected the gay or bisexual men tested were infected at a 
rate of 165 percent 
health officials dont have a real good handle on the number 
of people who have been tested at private physicians offices not 
participating in the publicly funded aids programs bowen said 
such tests are not necessarily reported to health officials 
more than 120000 aids cases have been reported in the united 
states with more than 72000 deaths the cdc recommended efforts 
to ensure that even more people with undetected hiv infections 
receive testing and counseling 
