<TEXT>
the supreme courts nine members are among the 
most private of public officials they wield enormous political 
power but rarely hold news conferences or give interviews recent 
polls indicate only one in three americans can name any of the 
nine this the fourth in an occasional series offers an 
uptodate look at one member of the nations highest court 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
antonin scalia often seems impatient with the 
pace of change on an increasingly conservative supreme court but 
time could be on his side the comparatively youthful justice may 
be using his keen intellect and missionary zeal well into the 21st 
century to pull the court farther to the right 
the prospect delights conservatives and alarms liberals 
his supporters call him a man of principle unwilling to accept 
halfmeasures detractors say he is an extremist bent on undoing 
key liberal precedents 
both sides agree that scalia who turned 54 sunday and is 30 
years younger than the courts oldest member is assuming the role 
of conservative point man played by william h rehnquist before he 
became chief justice 
there is no question that since rehnquist has become chief 
justice he has seen his role as less of an advocate than a 
consensusbuilder a vacuum was created and scalia filled that 
void said rich samp of the conservative washington legal 
foundation 
scalias confrontational style was on display last year when 
justice sandra day oconnor stopped short of voting to overturn the 
courts 1973 ruling in roe vs wade that created a constitutional 
right to an abortion 
calling oconnors position irrational a frustrated scalia 
said we can now look forward to at least another term with carts 
full of mail from the public and streets full of demonstrators 
american university law professor herman schwartz said scalia 
an ardent foe of judicially created rights was showing his pique 
i think he was angry and i think he feels oconnor may have 
betrayed the cause and hes a man who believes in causes 
schwartz said 
judge abner mikva a former colleague on the federal appeals 
court here on which scalia served before former president reagan 
named him to the high court in 1986 has described scalia as warm 
and engaging and unyielding in fighting for what he believes 
he understands the doctrine of collegiality and has in fact 
found middle ground mikva said but once scalia has made up his 
mind theres no shaking him loose 
scalia sticking to his general policy declined to be 
interviewed for this article 
gregarious and quickwitted he normally revels in being the 
center of attention before a reception held for him by reporters 
when he joined the high court he said i can have more fun if 
its off the record 
assured he would not be quoted for publication he engaged in a 
lively dialogue for hours as reporters peppered him with questions 
on another occasion scalia was asked why he was wearing a 
tuxedo to an informal evening gettogether at the court 
he was headed for another party scalia said adding esteemed 
jurist by day manabouttown by night 
the same playfulness is apparent at the courts argument 
sessions the justices only regularly scheduled public appearances 
scalia is among the courts most forceful persistent and 
frequent interrogators of the lawyers who argue before the court 
using the attorneys as foils he often appears to be trying to 
persuade other justices to see his views 
sometimes the tactic backfires 
justice harry a blackmun said after the courts 198788 term 
that scalia asks far too many questions he takes over the case 
from counsel 
rehnquist once indirectly scolded scalia from the bench after 
the junior justice persisted in quizzing a lawyer about a 
procedural matter 
i hope when youre given an opportunity to do so youll 
address some of your remarks to the question on which the court 
voted to grant review rehnquist told the attorney 
scalias critics worry that he has an agenda for overruling past 
decisions particularly ones that expanded civil rights and 
individual liberties 
it is as though he made a list of all the things he didnt 
like that the court has done in the last 50 years said american 
universitys schwartz essentially he sees himself as the agent 
of major change to root out these constitutional errors in many 
ways hes the most radical member of the court 
but alan slobodin of the washington legal foundation said 
scalias only agenda is adhering to the original intent of the 
framers of the constitution and reducing judicial intervention in 
decisionmaking by the executive and legislative branches 
i might call him the originalist conscience of the court 
slobodin said hes less interested in votecounting than in 
forcing the justices to confront first principles hes trying to 
make the court more accountable more principled 
scalia the courts first italianamerican and father of nine 
children has a strong academic background he is the only son of 
an italian immigrant father who was a professor at brooklyn college 
and a mother who taught elementary school 
scalia graduated first in his class from georgetown university 
and won high honors with his harvard university law degree he 
taught law for 10 years 
the impact of his brilliance on the supreme court remains 
uncertain 
university of chicago law school dean geoffrey stone who 
admires scalias boldness said the thing to keep in mind about 
scalia is he does have very strong intellectual skills that will 
lead him to be out in front the real question is will there be 
anyone behind him 
</TEXT>
