<TEXT>
for years each school day lorraine begay was 
flung from side to side as the van from the local high school 
bumped over the 10 miles of rutted dirt roads leading to her navajo 
reservation home 
the girl crippled by severe arthritis wanted to attend a 
nearby federal bureau of indian affairs boarding school but the 
bureau would not install the wheelchair ramp and special toilet she 
needed 
ms begay still is being bounced around this time in federal 
court where she filed suit for unspecified damages after 
experiencing what one judge called bureaucracy at its worst 
because ms begay cannot sue the federal government directly 
she has sued individual bia employees ranging from an agency 
superintendent to a head custodian who face financial ruin if she 
wins their lawyers say 
both sides are hoping the federal government will reimburse the 
employees if ms begay wins a judgment but the government has 
refused any payments so far though it likely will spend more on 
attorneys fees than it would have cost to settle out of court 
in addition to the lawyers fees the government could be forced 
to reimburse the employees for whatever ms begay wins at trial 
us district judge carl muecke said in a january ruling that an 
assistant us attorney who represented them early in the 
litigation may have botched the case so badly that they will be 
able to sue the government for damages 
no trial date has been set and the case has dragged on for 
years despite general agreement that ms begay suffered 
unneccessarily 
the modifications the school needed to accommodate her 
wheelchair would have cost no more than a few thousand dollars at 
most according to court records and were supposed to have been 
made under a federal law mandating access for the handicapped 
school officials give conflicting reasons as to why the work 
wasnt done 
no records are available detailing how much the lawsuit has cost 
the government but one defense attorney estimates the legal bill 
for the four private lawyers alone already has reached 80000 and 
could double or triple if the case goes to trial 
ms begay now 23 graduated from high school two years late 
largely because of paininduced absences she still lives at home 
with no electricity or running water in the tiny community of many 
farms deep inside the sprawling navajo reservation 
arthritis has confined her to a wheelchair since age 13 and she 
often doesnt even have the muscle strength to sit up 
her mind is wasting away and thats all she has because her 
body obviously doesnt do much for her said pamela liberty who 
took on ms begays case while a legal aid attorney and stuck with 
it after moving to private practice 
were not trying to make this into a milliondollar lawsuit 
ms liberty said we want what it would take to get her through 
college 
ms begays problems began in 1980 but she tried to resolve 
them with school officials and did not file suit until july 1985 
she was offered placement in a distant school for the 
handicapped but chose to stay with her family and commute to the 
high school while waiting for the local boarding school to install 
the ramp and toilet 
as late as may 21 1985 she still hoped for an outofcourt 
resolution 
i am writing to you to see if you can help me go to school at 
many farms boarding high school she said in a handwritten letter 
to sen dennis deconcini dariz 
they say there is no ramp for my wheel chair she wrote 
they have told me they would fix the school up so i could go 
there but they never have 
i cry a lot because of pains from traveling the reservation 
roads thats why i want to go to a boarding school i do not want 
to go to a handicap school i am a regular child and want to be in 
school with all my brothers and sisters 
government officials made an offer 25000 according to 
sources relatively early in the case but ms begays lawyers 
wanted 100000 figuring thats what it would take to finance four 
years at a good outofstate college 
ms begays acceptable minimum has been rising as the legal 
maneuvers by defense attorneys continue ms libertys former boss 
at southern arizona legal aid bill morris now figures the minimum 
at 250000 
the judge has scoffed at defense claims that ms begay is to 
blame because she did not fill out applications after being told 
the school couldnt admit her 
the school telling her to forget it was like having somebody 
stand at the door with a gun muecke said 
of defense attorneys claims that only toplevel officials in 
washington are at fault the judge said i find that rather 
astonishing i find that bureaucracy at its worst 
i dont think any of the defendants have done anything 
wrong said dan rosenfelt an albuquerque nm lawyer who 
represents some of the employees including a school principal who 
says he never talked to ms begay and didnt even know about the 
problem 
its not clear that the government did anything wrong 
rosenfelt said this is not a case in my opinion where justice 
cries out for a settlement 
