<TEXT>
in 1954 volker schlondorff was a 15yearold 
living in wiesbaden west germany when he saw elia kazans film 
classic on the waterfront after the movie was over he walked 
out of the theater and kept walking for hours 
schlondorff couldnt stop thinking about how effective movies 
were at showing injustice in the world how well he related to 
marlon brandos fight against corrupt union officials how film 
seemed larger than life yet completely believeable 
the same week schlondorff saw alfred hitchcocks thriller 
rear window and took another walk this time he thought of 
suspense watching and being watched of james stewart unable to 
move out of his wheelchair because of a broken leg making up 
stories about the neighbors on whom he spied 
idealism and voyeurism have been a major part of the directors 
own work never more effectively than in the 1979 film the tin 
drum schlondorffs acclaimed adaptation of gunter grass novel 
about nazi germany as seen through a young boys eyes 
so schlondorff had no difficulty agreeing to direct the movie 
version of margaret atwoods bestselling the handmaids tale 
in which a young woman natasha richardson in the movie observes 
and eventually escapes the horrors of gilead a society ruled 
by rightwing fundamentalists 
while we were doing it we were strongly reminded of the tin 
drum schlondorff said in a recent interview 
the main character of natasha richardson and the way she goes 
through life first trying to understand before even reacting the 
socalled passive character as if to watch and to think wasnt an 
activity is very similar to tin drum where hes mostly the 
witness of whats happening to others and whats happening to 
himself 
in gilead women live in a strict caste system their rank 
indicated by the color of their clothes richardson dressed in 
red is a handmaid her sole function to conceive children robert 
duvall is the commander whose child richardson is to bear faye 
dunaway is his wife and aidan quinn is the commanders chauffeur 
with whom richardson falls in love 
schlondorff viewed the characters as archetypes representing 
different aspects of society the patriarch the matriarch etc 
and thought the story had an epic structure in line with the 
operas he loves to produce 
the whole idea that every character has his aria then from 
time to time theres an ensemble piece and its important to have 
changes of pace you can not be fast all the time he said 
there is also the idea of a crescendo and a high point i like 
to work on screenplays some times in terms of music thinking of 
music and to get the musicians involved in it 
schlondorff emerged in the mid1960s as part of the junger 
deutscher film movement young german film movement which 
included rainer werner fassbinder werner herzog and wim wenders 
his first feature film young torless came out in 1966 and 
shared the international critics prize at cannes he has since 
directed the lost honor of katharina blum and coup de 
grace among others and also directed the american television 
adaptation of death of a salesman which starred dustin hoffman 
schlondorff begins his 1981 film circle of deceit with an 
explanation to the audience that the film about the civil war in 
lebanon is just a work of the imagination only fictional though 
the scenes were shot on location 
the handmaids tale is also a work of the imagination of 
course but schlondorff had little trouble finding a realistic 
setting for a society that supposedly doesnt exist 
we said what would an american dictatorship be like first 
of all it would be run by advertising people who would try to make 
the most gruesome things look comfortable 
this future society would be a cheap society a k mart 
society you wind up with a world of supermarkets and shopping 
malls and then you go to north carolina and you say well its 
all there so we gave up all this big elaboration and said 
lets just shoot the existing world and say its our future 
schlondorff considers each of his films a personal creation no 
matter who first developed the story noting that atwood began the 
book in berlin the director adds his own touch including a 
reconstruction of the berlin wall in the opening scene 
i think culture has to do not with reinventing from scratch 
all the time but with reflections and variations on things other 
people did before we are just in a chain of people working again 
and again with the same material it may seem minor to some people 
but its major enough for me 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

