<TEXT>
debt experts testifying about junk bonds 
before a house panel looked at their tea leaves and said things 
will get better unless they get worse 
they also suggested congress shouldnt try to restrict junk 
bonds even though they predicted more companies are likely to 
default on their obligations 
representatives from the venerable bond rating agencies moodys 
investors service and standard amp poors corp were among the 
witnesses testifying thursday before a subcommittee of the house 
energy and commerce committee 
while the credithappy 1980s saw corporations leverage their 
operations heavily by taking on ever more debt deleveraging is 
the future trend of the early 1990s said mark bachman senior 
vice president of sampps corporate finance department 
unfortunately there are reasons to be concerned that the 
process of deleveraging may not proceed smoothly he added the 
main reason the economy 
while a mild recession would not necessarily pose major 
problems a severe one could said bachman 
an sampp publication released earlier this week said us 
companies defaulted on 6 billion of publicly issued debt last 
year up from 44 billion in 1988 annual defaults could 
approach 15 billion in a difficult economic environment it 
predicted 
the congressional testimony provided a shortcourse in corporate 
finance especially concerning the highyield highrisk bonds 
dubbed junk 
a junk bond is a shaky debt it is the promise to pay of a 
debtor who is just getting by said james grant editor of 
grants interest rate observer 
most bonds are in effect corporate ious promising to pay back 
borrowed money at a later date while paying a regular fixed 
interest 
junk bonds however are considered by agencies like sampp and 
moodys to be speculative carrying a significant risk of default 
to compensate for the greater risk they pay a much higher rate of 
interest than more stable bonds 
proponents of junk bonds says that the high yields more than 
compensate for the risk of default if your portfolio is 
diversified 
pioneered by financier michael milken at nowdefunct drexel 
burnham lambert inc junk bonds helped small or fledgling 
companies expand and also assisted corporate raiders take over huge 
corporations with little or no cash 
but the 200 billion junk bond market has been rocked repeatedly 
in recent months by milkens indictment on racketeering charges 
corporate defaults the withdrawal of many savings and loan 
institutions as buyers and the bankruptcy filing by drexels parent 
company 
thomas j mcguire director of moodys corporate department 
said the default rate for junk bonds has risen to 54 percent 
the secondhighest rate since 1970 and the outlook given the 
increase in lower rated issuers and the potentially unfavorable 
economic environment is for still higher levels of defaults in 
the early 1990s 
a jittery market and the selfdestruction of drexel burnham 
lambert group have raised new questions about the role of junk 
bonds in our economy said rep edward markey dmass chairman 
of the telecommunications and finance subcommittee 
is there anything for congress to do about this markey 
asked 
not necessarily economists said 
legislation is more likely to worsen than help the problem 
said david a wyss chief financial economist for drimcgrawhill 
leverage is a response to the incentives in the tax law and 
unless those incentives change attacking the symptoms will just 
cause problems elsewhere he said 
moreover wyss said if investors can hold on to the bonds for 
an extended period riding through the current storm we believe 
their patience will be rewarded 
the junk bond problem is really a junk credit problem said 
grant a prominent critic of the growth of debt in recent years 
in the 1980s we had an explosion of the credit supply 
with the junk market battered by the developments of recent 
months i would advise the subcommittee to be wary of pushing the 
market toward even greater stringency grant said 
</TEXT>
