<TEXT>
government plans to increase taxes and 
regulation on futures trading are death threats that could 
imperil the industry the head of the worlds biggest futures 
exchange says 
in a speech thursday to the annual meeting of the futures 
industry association chicago board of trade chairman karsten 
mahlmann said americas share of worldwide futures trading volume 
has dropped by 175 percent over the last five years 
proposals to restrict and tax futures trading will make overseas 
exchanges even more attractive he said 
during a panel discussion mahlmann and officials of the chicago 
mercantile exchange and the new york mercantile exchange complained 
about several proposals including 
a plan by the commodity futures trading commission to restrict 
dual trading 
a bush administration proposal for an 11cent fee on every 
futures trade to fund increased cftc surveillance of futures 
markets 
a push by the securities and exchange commission to gain 
regulatory authority over stockindex futures a market that is now 
regulated by the cftc 
the proposals grew out of the federal investigation of futures 
trading fraud in chicago and the stock market crash of october 1987 
mahlmann said he too is seeking a healthier environment in 
which to conduct business but one in which we can work with 
our regulators rather than one in which we stand the distinct 
possibility of being killed 
chicago mercantile exchange president william brodsky and new 
york mercantile exchange chairman lou gutterman also lashed out at 
the cftcs dualtrading proposal 
brodsky told cftc chairman wendy gramm who also sat on the 
discussion panel in this particular case you used a 
sledgehammer instead of a scapel 
mrs gramm avoided the dualtrading controversy in her remarks 
instead she urged the industry to fight harder to keep regulation 
of stockindex futures under the cftcs jurisdiction and away from 
the sec 
the sec which oversees stock trading has been gaining 
congressional support for its view that the stock and stockindex 
futures markets are so closely linked that they should be regulated 
by one agency 
dual trading is the practice among floor brokers of trading for 
their own accounts after executing any orders from their public 
customers 
critics contend dual trading enables floor brokers to take 
advantageous market positions ahead of large customer orders that 
they know are likely to move prices that illegal practice known 
as frontrunning is among the fraud schemes alleged in the 
indictments of 48 traders at the board of trade and the chicago 
merc 
but futures exchange officials maintain that dual trading 
increases the efficiency of their markets by increasing the number 
of buyers and sellers 
since november the cftc has been gathering public comments on 
its proposals for a test ban on dual trading in selected markets 
regardless of the exchanges ability to detect fraud 
the cftc plan is based on an agency study that found no 
statistical support for the exchanges claims that dual trading 
increases market liquidity 
exchange officials involved in the panel discussion cited other 
studies that dispute the cftcs findings 
mahlmann said the board of trade opposes any restrictions on 
dual trading even so he said the cftc proposal is especially 
galling 
the cftc plan to ban dual trading has no basis in fact he 
said it appears to be designed for the sake of political 
expediency rather than logic 
the chicago merc has voluntarily restricted dual trading in one 
of its most active markets the standard amp poors 500 stockindex 
futures pit 
brodsky said the merc supports a cftc reauthorization bill 
passed last year by the house of representatives that would ban 
dual trading in the most active futures markets but would allow it 
to resume at exchanges that have a failsafe system for detecting 
abuses a similar measure is pending in the senate 
the merc and the board of trade are working together to develop 
an electronic trading card that would replace the paper cards 
on which traders record their trades such a system the exchanges 
say would create a foolproof means of detecting dualtrading 
abuses 
 
</TEXT>
