<TEXT>
greyhound lines incs hiring of replacements for 
its striking bus drivers reflects a trend toward tougher management 
stances in labor squabbles and some experts say the hardball 
tactics will make it harder to settle the weekold walkout 
hiring replacements is far different from the old strikes we 
used to have said mark kahn a labor arbitrator and professor 
emeritus at wayne state university in detroit 
in the past he said there has been a clearcut understanding 
that whenever the dispute is ironed out those workers will go back 
to work and the company will resume its operations that tends to 
create a relatively civilized atmosphere in which answers can be 
worked out 
replacements are indicative of some of the more bitter 
confrontational disputes that we are seeing said mike jadell an 
arbitrator and a professor at georgia state university in atlanta 
its become an additional tool in the arsenal of those 
employers who feel that they are in adversarial relationships he 
said 
some labor experts trace the confrontational approach to the 
start of the probusiness reagan administration and its decision in 
1981 to fire striking air traffic controllers and replace them with 
new hires 
greyhounds strategy is similar to that of eastern airlines 
which sought to rebuild as a smaller carrier with lower costs by 
hiring new nonunion workers after its machinists pilots and 
flight attendants struck a year ago 
we dont have a lot of options said p anthony lannie 
greyhounds executive vice president and chief negotiator this 
union has us backed into a corner 
the attimes violent strike began early march 2 when the 
amalgamated council of greyhound local unions and the company 
failed to reach agreement on a new threeyear contract the union 
represents 9435 of greyhounds 11825 employees including 6300 
drivers 1600 office workers and 1475 maintenance workers 
the company says it can afford no more than its original 63 
million offer the union says its last proposal is less than 
greyhounds but the company values it at 205 million 
there has been little contact between the two sides since 
although federal mediators thursday asked for a factfinding 
meeting with the union next week followed by a similar session with 
the company 
greyhound has been operating at reduced levels since the strike 
using replacements hired and trained in the last two weeks plus any 
union members who cross picket lines 
lannie said thursday 800 permanent replacements plus an 
additional 368 union drivers are behind the wheels of the 
companys buses the company says it received more than 6500 
applications for jobs and will be able to operate a full schedule 
by the end of the month 
in other words a total of 3468 of the most junior people 
that are striking right now do not have jobs he said 
because demand is expected to be lower immediately after the 
strike lannie said the company will need fewer drivers initially 
leaving only about 2000 regular fulltime openings left to be 
filled 
the union has vowed to regain the jobs for its members 
when management is prepared to enter into good faith 
negotiations their union will ensure that their jobs and seniority 
are secured said union spokesman jeffrey nelson 
the management team that took over the only nationwide bus 
service three years ago is taking a much harsher stance than its 
predecessors 
in a 47day walkout in 1983 greyhound then owned by 
phoenixbased conglomerate greyhound corp hired replacements 
during the strike but then fired them to make room for returning 
union members 
experts say the companys new position is bolstered by events 
since then including a supreme court decision last year concerning 
a strike against trans world airlines inc that decision upheld a 
companys right to keep union members who crossed pickets lines 
lannie said 
most companies have had the right to hire replacements for 
decades although few exercised it kahn said 
its a very contentious issue he said its a way an 
employer can beat the strike but its the antithesis of sensible 
and rational efforts to resolve the dispute 
the outcomes got to be very bad especially for the employees 
who lose their jobs 
the use of replacements also raises the stakes for the union he 
said and makes it far more difficult for the union to agree to a 
settlement under which many of its members wont come back to 
work 
two bills have been introduced in congress that would limit the 
use of permanent replacements but kahn and others doubted they 
would pass 
just wednesday the house failed to override president bushs 
veto of a bill to create a commission on the yearold eastern 
airlines strike 
replacement workers also have been used international paper co 
boise cascade phelps dodge and easterns sister carrier 
continental airlines 
charles m rehmus a labor law professor at the university of 
san diego said it was the 1981 air controllers strike that gave 
replacements legitimacy 
it encouraged employers generally to operate through a strike 
and employees to cross picket lines he said 
</TEXT>
