gaf corp facing up to 4 million in fines 
on a criminal conviction for stock manipulation has agreed to pay 
125 million plus interest to settle related civil charges 
involving the trading of union carbide corp stock 
gaf and its vice chairman james t sherwin did not admit or 
deny allegations in the civil complaint which alleged that it 
manipulated the price of union carbide stock in 1986 
the chemical manufacturer and sherwin were to be sentenced today 
in new york for their criminal conviction 
sherwin 56 faces up to 40 years in prison and up to 2 million 
in fines but a jail term is not expected to approach the maximum 
term 
gaf a new jerseybased chemical and building materials 
manufacturer could be fined as much as 4 million as a convicted 
felon it also could be forced to sell its classical radio station 
in new york city wncnfm 
under the civil settlement filed thursday in federal court in 
washington dc gaf and sherwin consented to injunctions that 
prevented them from manipulating stock 
the company agreed to pay 125 million plus interest dating 
from oct 30 1986 to the securities and exchange commission the 
funds will be placed in escrow for investors who were affected by 
gafs actions sec enforcement division attorney kevin mcenery said 
the settlement was made with the sec in order to resolve this 
matter promptly and avoid protracted and costly litigation gaf 
said in a statement company officials declined to comment further 
the sec and a federal grand jury accused sherwin and gaf of 
manipulating the price of union carbide stock in collaboration with 
former stockbroker boyd l jefferies in october 1986 they sought 
to push up the share price before selling a large block gaf had 
amassed in a failed takeover attempt the complaint alleged 
after two mistrials gaf and sherwin were convicted in manhattan 
federal court in december of eight counts of stock manipulation 
securities fraud wire fraud and conspiracy two gaf subsidiaries 
were acquitted 
the conviction marked the first time that a company off wall 
street was convicted in the governments insider trading 
investigation that stemmed from disclosures by former stock 
speculator ivan boesky who paid 100 million in fines and was 
sentenced to three years in prison 
lawyers for sherwin and gaf have said they plan to appeal 
the case initially attracted wide attention as the first 
criminal trial in the governments securities fraud and insider 
trading crackdown in the 1980s but dragged on through 1989 and was 
upstaged by other cases 
in the case jefferies testified he agreed to bid up the price 
of union carbide at sherwins request gaf was trying to sell five 
million union carbide shares after the takeover for the larger 
chemicals concern failed 
the sec said the 125 million represents certain benefits 
received by gaf as a result of purchases of union carbide stock by 
jefferies amp co jefferies securities firm 
the government alleged that sherwin and jefferies agreed to have 
jefferies close the price of the common stock of union carbide at 
22 or higher and sherwin agreed to compensate jefferies for any 
losses 
