<TEXT>
the soviet union has formally applied for observer 
status with the general agreement on tariffs and trade a spokesman 
for the 96nation world trade forum said friday 
david woods said evgeny makeyev soviet ambassador in geneva 
submitted the application thursday and asked that the request be 
considered at the next gatt council meeting scheduled for april 3 
observer status would enable the soviet union to examine gatt 
and the preconditions for full membership while also keeping 
trading partners up to date with moscows economic restructuring 
program woods said 
members of the marketorientated organization which draws up 
agreements to liberalize global commerce and mediates trade 
disputes account for more than fourfifths of world trade 
diplomats who spoke on condition of anonymity said there was 
wide support for moscow to become involved in gatt before the end 
of the year but they added the application was unlikely to be 
approved as quickly as next month 
although observer status would not automatically entitle the 
soviet union to multilateral trading concessions enjoyed by full 
gatt members it would give moscow firsthand knowledge of changes 
in the world trading system such information is necessary to back 
up soviet economic and trade reforms 
but the soviet union would not be privy to talks on 
comprehensive new agreements to liberalize trade in areas such as 
agriculture and textiles that are being drawn up as part of the 
ambitious uruguay round of negotiations scheduled to end in 
december 
around 30 countries are observers at gatt including china 
which is seeking full membership 
at last decembers malta summit us president george bush said 
he would back moscows bid for observer status the united states 
had previously opposed any soviet involvement on the grounds that 
the soviet economic system was incompatible with gatts free trade 
principles 
</TEXT>
