<TEXT>
sen richard lugar the ranking republican on 
the senate agriculture committee introduced a farm bill friday 
that would freeze at current levels the target prices for crops 
regulated by the government 
the measure reflects most of the proposals laid out in february 
by the bush administration for the 1990 farm bill 
it goes a step further however by speaking to target prices 
which the administration avoided 
financial analysts have said that even keeping the prices steady 
could push the farm bill beyond the administrations proposed 
budget depending on the world commodities market 
we may need to find savings in agricultural programs this 
year but we cannot yet estimate how much said lugar rind 
my purpose today is to introduce a farm bill and not a budget 
reconciliation bill 
he said his bill had no price tag but estimated it could cost 
less than the approximately 10 billion currently spent on 
agriculture programs if market conditions are right and no weather 
disaster occurs 
target prices are what the government decides a farmer should 
get in the marketplace for wheat corn sorghum barley oats rice 
and upland and extralong staple cotton these commodities often 
are called program crops because farmers that grow them 
participate in the federal commodities program 
if the market price is below the governments target price the 
government pays the farmer the difference known as a deficiency 
payment 
congress sets target prices every five years when it passes a 
farm bill lawmakers say they want to send the 1990 legislation to 
the president by the end of the summer 
lugars bill which also emphasizes flexible planting options 
for farmers who grow program crops is similar to legislation 
introduced wednesday by sen rudy boschwitz rminn another 
member of the agriculture committee 
boschwitz calls his bill the farm flexibility act of 1990 it 
also calls for a freeze on target prices 
flexibility has been stressed by agriculture secretary clayton 
yeutter in promoting the administrations proposals he says the 
government will save money on deficiency payments if farmers are 
allowed to let market demand determine their planting decisions 
his proposals and the lugar and boschwitz bills safeguard farm 
income by allowing the farmer to collect deficiency payments based 
on whatever program crop dominates the acreage even if the market 
losses are on another crop the farmer has decided to experiment 
with that year 
yeutter says farmers also would be encouraged to rotate crops 
which will be good for the soil and reduce the need for chemicals 
today rigid planting rules often lock farmers into planting 
the same crop on the same land year after year said lugar 
past farm legislation has encouraged planting of socalled 
program crops such as corn even when market demand calls for 
more production of nonprogram crops such as soybeans as a result 
the united states loses foreign markets 
boschwitz said he came up with his proposal after holding 150 
meetings on farms across minnesota 
farmers have told me that they would enjoy having the freedom 
to adjust their crop mix in response to the market and consumer 
demands boschwitz said 
he and lugar said farmers are happy with the 1985 law both 
senators said their bills would basically extend that law 
an aide to sen patrick leahy dvt chairman of the 
agriculture committee said many committee members will be 
introducing farm bills this month 
they all will be placed together for review of the committee and 
debate over which provisions from each should be part of the final 
bill voted on by the senate the aide said 
</TEXT>
