<TEXT>
the white house on friday emphatically denied 
a report that president bush was mad as hell at alan greenspan 
but some private economists said the federal reserve chairman was 
being given a blunt message to lower interest rates or risk losing 
his job 
the los angeles times in its friday editions quoted a longtime 
bush adviser as saying greenspans refusal to further lower 
interest rates made it extremely unlikely greenspan would be 
reappointed fed chairman when his term expires in august 1991 
the unidentified adviser said bush was mad as hell over 
greenspans position and the adviser was also quoted as saying i 
cant believe bush will reappoint him and i dont know a soul in 
the white house who thinks he will 
white house press secretary marlin fitzwater denied bush was 
angry with greenspan michael boskin the presidents chief 
economic adviser said there was no foundation for the story which 
he termed out of left field 
however boskin stopped short of endorsing the feds current 
policies and he also refused to say whether he would recommend that 
greenspan be reappointed calling that question premature 
various administration officials have publicly criticized the 
fed over the past several months but the times story was the first 
to suggest bush was so upset that greenspans reappointment was 
unlikely 
at the fed spokeswoman marci schneider said greenspan would 
have no comment on the times story 
but many private economists said they believed the unnamed bush 
adviser was sending a clear warning that greenspan needs to relent 
his tightmoney policies in order to spur economic growth which 
dipped in the last quarter to its most sluggish pace in more than 
three years 
the administration thinks that greenspan is screwing up the 
economy they believe that if only greenspan would lower interest 
rates we would have faster growth a lower budget deficit and 
everybody would be better off said michael evans head of a 
washington forecasting firm 
former federal reserve chairman paul volcker greenspans 
predecessor was the target of similar barbed comments in 1983 when 
his first term as chairman was expiring 
you never know on these whether they are trial balloons from 
some disgruntled element in the administration that wants to get 
rid of greenspan or whether bush is really mad said david wyss 
chief financial economist at drimcgraw hill i remember a lot of 
similar stories right about the time reagan reappointed volcker 
but other analysts said reagan was forced to reappoint volcker 
in 1983 because jittery financial markets had a lot of faith in 
volckers ability to manage the economy they said greenspan may 
not command the same amount of respect 
us financial markets seemed to ignore the entire flap on 
friday preferring to focus instead on the unemployment report 
which showed the jobless rate holding steady at 53 percent as job 
growth registered its biggest gain in 20 months 
analysts said the job growth supported greenspans current view 
that the danger point for a recession has passed and the economy 
should exhibit a modest rebound in coming months 
why would you lower interest rates when the economy seems to 
be pushing ahead you would just be running grave risks of making 
inflation worse said robert dederick chief economist of northern 
trust co of chicago 
