<TEXT>
aftershocks from president bushs savings and 
loan bailout are rippling across the financial and political 
landscapes touching for better or worse millions of americans 
taxpayers are hurting even if they dont know it money spent 
on savings institutions wont be available for education the drug 
war and other worthy purposes 
in its first six months the new bailout agency the resolution 
trust corp has spent 24 billion and thats just a down payment 
sophisticated savers who put their money in shaky sampls paying 
high interest rates are hurting too an infusion of government 
money into sampls has pulled those rates down 
others are benefiting however a booming new scavenger industry 
is rising from the ashes of the savings and loans 
although the rtc aims at a payroll of 4800 people by the end of 
the year up from 2300 now most of its work will be performed by 
private contractors 
more than 10000 accountants lawyers real estate brokers 
appraisers and property managers have queried the rtc and are 
waiting eagerly for the spring when the agency begins awarding an 
estimated 15 billion worth of contracts 
the pickings are particularly juicy for lawyers the rtc already 
is involved in 40000 lawsuits inherited from its bureaucratic 
predecessors or the sampls its taking over 
according to rtc chairman l william seidman that likely will 
double requiring help from 500 outside law firms 
commercial banks are beneficiaries of the bill as well in the 
vast majority of government thrift deals to date banks have been 
the buyers expanding their retail branch networks 
also as sampls make fewer loans banks have moved to replace 
them in the third quarter of last year residential mortgage 
lending at banks surpassed sampl mortgage lending for the first time 
banks had 38 percent of the market compared with 35 percent for 
thrift associations 
both banks and sampls but not savers are being helped by a 
program to reduce deposit rates paid by the institutions under 
government control the rtc has replaced 92 billion in highcost 
deposits with government money and expects to spend another 3 
billion in march 
as a result pressure has eased on healthy sampls and banks once 
forced to offer high rates to compete against insolvent but open 
institutions according to an office of thrift supervision study 
meanwhile developers complain that one provision of the 
legislation is having the unintended effect of choking off credit 
for worthy projects the law sharply reduced the maximum loan an 
institution can make to a single lender from 100 percent of net 
worth to 15 percent 
it was intended to force thrifts to diversify their risks but 
builders say even good loans arent being made 
the culprits of the crisis both politicians and sampl executives 
also are beginning to suffer 
the rtc has referred 1200 cases of suspected fraud to the 
justice department in texas alone 500 individuals are targeted 
for investigation according to mark m richard deputy assistant 
attorney general 
meanwhile five senators who intervened with regulators on 
behalf of millionaire charles h keating jrs lincoln savings and 
loan association are sweating through a senate ethics committee 
