<DOCNO> AP900309-0271 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
two drugs used to treat heart attacks save lives 
equally well despite a 10fold difference in their cost according 
to research announced thursday 
the risk of dying before leaving the hospital was the same no 
matter whether the patient was treated with streptokinase or tissue 
plasminogen activator called tpa 
when each drug was combined with a second drug called heparin 
streptokinase showed a lower death rate 
but an official of genentech inc the major biotechnology 
company that makes tpa the more expensive drug said he believes 
the study was not the final answer for american doctors 
the results released at a medical conference in florence 
italy dealt with more than 20000 european heart attack patients 
the researchers were from italy and elsewhere in europe 
the study found an overall death rate of 89 percent after 
treatment with tpa and an 85 percent rate after treatment with 
streptokinase statistically those rates are the same 
both drugs are designed to destroy blood clots that have caused 
heart attacks by blocking a crucial blood vessel 
genentechs tpa holds about twothirds of the market while 
streptokinase has about a third genentech reported tpa sales of 
197 million in 1989 
but their costs vary greatly an editorial in the new england 
journal of medicine last year said one treatment with streptokinase 
costs 78 at a san francisco hospital while tpa costs 2268 a 
separate report has cited a 10fold difference 
the new england journal editorial accompanied a study that 
suggested the two drugs worked equally well but it looked at the 
health of the hearts main pumping chamber rather than death rates 
the newly announced study bears out what a number of 
cardiologists have been really saying for the last four or five 
years that there has been absolutely no scientific evidence that 
tpa was superior to streptokinase said an american investigator 
familiar with the results william oneill of william beaumont 
hospital in royal oak mich 
but david stump director of clinical research for genentech 
said the trials treatment procedure hampered the effectiveness of 
tpa 
patients did not receive early intravenous doses of heparin 
along with tpa therapy he said many american doctors take that 
step to keep opened arteries from becoming obstructed again he 
said 
the heparin given some patients in the study was administered 
much later in the course of therapy and through injections under 
the skin rather than intravenously he said in a telephone 
interview from florence 
the combination of tpa plus heparin in the new study gave a 
death rate of 92 percent and streptokinase plus heparin yielded a 
79 percent rate 
g kirk raab president and chief executive officer of 
genentech called for further tests of patients who got early 
intravenous injections of heparin 
the study wont affect a planned merger between genentech and 
roche holding ltd the swiss pharmaceutical giant that was 
announced last month according to a roche news release 
individual trials limited to certain aspects only would not 
influence such important investment decisions roche said 
the study also found the risk of stroke was greater in patients 
treated with tpa the stroke rate was 13 percent among the group 
treated with tpa compared with 1 percent in those treated with 
streptokinase 
these stroke rates are within the 1 percent to 15 percent 
range seen in other studies with thrombolytics antiblood cloting 
drugs and are within the range seen in heart attack patients not 
receiving thrombolytic therapy genentech said in a statement 
